coredata.dc:description:
An efficient and robust bifunctional catalyst that is comprised of tungsten nitride quantum dots encapsulated in ultrathin graphene (WN@C) is synthesized by in situ nitridation reduced pyrolysis method. The photocatalytic and co-catalytic effects of core-shell WN@C are systematically studied. After combining with typical semiconductor ZnIn2S4, the hydrogen evolution activity of the optimal WN@C/ZnIn2S4 composite exhibits 61 times larger than that of ZnIn2S4 and 12 times than that of WN-QDs@C under the visible light illumination (λ ≥ 400 nm). It can continuously produce hydrogen for 99 h without apparent reduction. The analysis and calculations suggest that the enhanced activity can be attributed to the synergistic effect of the lower overpotential of hydrogen evolution reaction (HER), the reduced apparent activation energy (E

      a
   ), the decreased Gibbs free energy of H adsorption (∆G

      *H
   ) and the inhibited recombination of photocharges. This work opens an avenue of the synthesis on quantum dots core-shell structure with dual functions.

ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
An efficient and robust bifunctional catalyst that is comprised of tungsten nitride quantum dots encapsulated in ultrathin graphene (WN@C) is synthesized by in situ nitridation reduced pyrolysis method. The photocatalytic and co-catalytic effects of core-shell WN@C are systematically studied. After combining with typical semiconductor ZnIn2S4, the hydrogen evolution activity of the optimal WN@C/ZnIn2S4 composite exhibits 61 times larger than that of ZnIn2S4 and 12 times than that of WN-QDs@C under the visible light illumination (λ ≥ 400 nm). It can continuously produce hydrogen for 99 h without apparent reduction. The analysis and calculations suggest that the enhanced activity can be attributed to the synergistic effect of the lower overpotential of hydrogen evolution reaction (HER), the reduced apparent activation energy (E

                        a
                     ), the decreased Gibbs free energy of H adsorption (∆G

                        *H
                     ) and the inhibited recombination of photocharges. This work opens an avenue of the synthesis on quantum dots core-shell structure with dual functions.

ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the above analysis, the photocatalysis mechanism is proposed as follows (Fig. 7c). When the visible light irradiates, the photo-induced electrons can inject into the empty conduction band (CB) of ZnIn2S4, leaving the positive holes in its valence band (VB). Due to the Fermi level difference, the direction of built-in electric field (BIEF) is from positively charged carbon shell to negatively charged ZnIn2S4 (shown in Fig. 7c). The BIEF can facilitate the photo-induced electrons flow from CB of ZnIn2S4 to the WN@C, while the holes on VB react with sacrificial agent. In the long-wavelength light irradiation, the WN QDs mainly play the role of co-catalyst because of the severe up-bending band and lack of energetic electrons. While under short wavelength light, WN-QDs can be utilized as an efficient photocatalyst due to the enormous energetic carriers. Compared with graphene, the WN-QDs shows better co-catalytic effect, which implies that the active sites locate at the surface of WN-QDs. Hence, the ultrathin and nano-sized graphene shell acts as a high-speed channel for transporting charges and extremely shortens the transportation distance. This makes it possible for the system to transfer electrons to the active sites of WN quickly and utilize the photo-induced electrons effectively by numerous WN-QDs. The intense contact between ZnIn2S4 and graphene is connected through the ZnC bond, which is helpful for the charges transfer. The graphene shell is indispensable for encapsulating WN QDs into separate part, preventing from the agglomeration of nanoparticles. Hence, this well-designed structure shows largely enhanced photocatalytic performance and ultra-long stability. The different parameters of ZnIn2S4 and the optimal composite are shown in 
                        Table 1. Kinetic studies and calculations demonstrate that the core-shell WN@C can sharply decrease the apparent activation energy (E

                           a
                        ) of the reaction, the overpotential of hydrogen evolution and the Gibbs free energy (∆G

                           *H
                        ) of HER. Besides, photoelectrochemical tests confirm that the increased lifetime and enhancing separation of charge carriers are also responsible for the good photocatalytic performance.
